###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AreaCoveredBySnow
ecv:AreaCoveredBySnow rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                               ecv:ecv-product ;
                      qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloM2 ;
                      ecv:isProductOf ecv:Snow ;
                      skos:definition "The area of snow-covered land, land ice, or firn." ;
                      skos:note "Area covered by snow can be determined from satellite observations and modeled. Unlike SWE and HS, area covered by snow cannot be calculated directly from in situ point measurements. Area can be calculated from binary and fractional products including, but not limited to, snow_area_fraction_viewable_from_above, surface_snow_area_fraction, and surface_snow_binary_mask. Temporal frequency requirements are for climate monitoring and do not preclude more frequent observations. Horizontal resolution requirements are for climate monitoring and do not preclude finer spatial resolutions. Due to the greater depth and higher variability of snow in mountain environments, we specify separate horizontal resolution and uncertainty values for mountain and non-mountain environments. Additionally, breakthrough horizontal resolutions are specified for specific use cases [1]." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Atmosphere
ecv:Atmosphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                        ecv:ecv-domain .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericComposition
ecv:AtmosphericComposition rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-subdomain ;
                           skos:member ecv:Atmosphere .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericPressure-nearSurface
ecv:AtmosphericPressure-nearSurface rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                                    qudt:hasUnit unit:HectoPA ;
                                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:SurfacePressure ;
                                    skos:definition "Air pressure at a known height above the surface with the height specified in the metadata." ;
                                    skos:note "Observations made over the ocean are not static, being mostly recorded by mobile ships and drifting buoys (Kent et al., 2019). Requirements for marine surface observations must therefore be defined in terms of the composite accuracy and sampling of the marine observing networks to achieve comparable uncertainty thresholds at similar resolution. The primary application of pressure in monitoring relates to the use of reanalysis and so these requirements have been set in this regard. Timeliness does not preclude delayed mode acquisition via e.g. data rescue. Important also, but not covered in the table, is the observation location information. A mis-placed observation of surface pressure (particularly the station elevation) will have substantial implications for reanalysis applications." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericTemperatureInTheBoundaryLayer
ecv:AtmosphericTemperatureInTheBoundaryLayer rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                      ecv:ecv-product ;
                                             qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                                             ecv:isProductOf ecv:Upper-airTemperature ;
                                             skos:definition "3D field of the atmospheric temperature in the Boundary Layer." ;
                                             skos:note "The following requirements are inferred mainly from the viewpoint of reanalysis and its near-real- time continuation in operational analyses as well as with respect to the magnitude of typical temperature variations at relevant spatial and temporal scales. Some additional considerations are also made, for which explanations are given in notes below this table. The requirements for temperature in the boundary layer are mainly driven by needs for monitoring of fluxes for the goal threshold. Stability assumes independence of measurements between instruments permitting partial cancellation and is based upon need to be able to detect current trends which are c.0.2 K/decade. Boundary layer temperature is assumed to share spatial characteristics with surface temperature for which this has been characterized in e.g. Thorne et al., 2018." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericTemperatureInTheFreeTroposphere
ecv:AtmosphericTemperatureInTheFreeTroposphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                        ecv:ecv-product ;
                                               qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                                               ecv:isProductOf ecv:Upper-airTemperature ;
                                               skos:definition "3D field of the atmospheric temperature in the troposphere." ;
                                               skos:note "The following requirements are inferred mainly from the viewpoint of reanalysis and its near-real-time continuation in operational analyses as well as with respect to the magnitude of typical temperature variations at relevant spatial and temporal scales. Some additional considerations are also made, for which explanations are given in notes below this table." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericTemperatureInTheMesosphere
ecv:AtmosphericTemperatureInTheMesosphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                   ecv:ecv-product ;
                                          qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                                          ecv:isProductOf ecv:Upper-airTemperature ;
                                          skos:definition "3D field of the atmospheric temperature in the mesosphere." ;
                                          skos:note "The following requirements are inferred mainly from the viewpoint of reanalysis and its near-real- time continuation in operational analyses as well as with respect to the magnitude of typical temperature variations at relevant spatial and temporal scales. Horizontal resolution, vertical resolution, temporal sampling, and uncertainty thresholds are based on the scales and amplitudes of typical dynamical features of the mesosphere. Trends and current uncertainties are larger than in the troposphere, so stability criteria can also be relaxed." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericTemperatureInTheMiddleAndUpperStratosphere
ecv:AtmosphericTemperatureInTheMiddleAndUpperStratosphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                                   ecv:ecv-product ;
                                                          qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                                                          ecv:isProductOf ecv:Upper-airTemperature ;
                                                          skos:definition "3D field of the atmospheric temperature in the middle and upper stratosphere." ;
                                                          skos:note "The following requirements are inferred mainly from the viewpoint of reanalysis and its near-real- time continuation in operational analyses as well as with respect to the magnitude of typical temperature variations at relevant spatial and temporal scales. Correlation distances on climate timescales are much larger in the stratosphere than the troposphere. The dynamical processes are distinct as is the degree of stratification which leads to lower requirements for both vertical and spatial resolution. Some large-scale waves are common to the upper stratosphere and lower mesosphere, with horizontal scales of around 2500 km. Historical and projected future trends are larger so commensurately the stability requirements can be relaxed accordingly." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#AtmosphericTemperatureInTheUpperTroposphereAndLowerStratosphere
ecv:AtmosphericTemperatureInTheUpperTroposphereAndLowerStratosphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                                                                    qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                                                                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:Upper-airTemperature ;
                                                                    skos:definition "3D field of the atmospheric temperature in the UTLS" ;
                                                                    skos:note "The following requirements are inferred mainly from the viewpoint of reanalysis and its near-real- time continuation in operational analyses as well as with respect to the magnitude of typical temperature variations at relevant spatial and temporal scales. Some additional considerations are also made, for which explanations are given in notes below this table. For vertical resolution, high vertical resolution is required to diagnose both multiple tropopauses but also trends in tropopause height." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#BareSoilEvaporation
ecv:BareSoilEvaporation rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                        qudt:hasUnit unit:W-PER-M2 ;
                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:EvaporationFromLand ;
                        skos:definition "The component of the total latent heat flux that corresponds to the direct evaporation of soil moisture into the atmosphere." ;
                        skos:note "The requirements are analogous to those of the total latent heat flux, because the applications are the same. Several studies have shown, however, that the accuracy of the latent heat flux can still be adequate despite a higher uncertainty in the evaporation components (i.e. bare soil evaporation, transpiration and interception loss) – see e.g. Miralles et al. (2016), Talsma et al. (2018). For that reason, the uncertainty goals have been subjectively relaxed based on expert judgement." .


