###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#ChemicalCompositionOfAerosolParticles
ecv:ChemicalCompositionOfAerosolParticles rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                   ecv:ecv-product ;
                                          qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroGM-PER-M3 ;
                                          ecv:isProductOf ecv:Aerosols ;
                                          skos:definition "Aerosol particles are chemically composed of inorganic salts (ammonium sulfates, ammonium nitrate, and sea salt), organic compounds, Elemental Carbon (EC), dust, and volcanic ash. These species are often internally mixed within a particle with mixtures depending on sources (primary particles and gas phase precursors), atmospheric processes (gas to particle conversion, cloud processing, and condensation), and atmospheric conditions (T, P, and RH). The chemical composition of aerosol particles is often expressed in μg m-3." ,
                                                          "Climate relevant properties of aerosol particles include hygroscopicity and refractive index. To a first approximation knowledge of the speciated amounts of key components (total inorganics – including sea-salt- , organics, Equivalent Black Carbon, mineral dust, and volcanic ash) is sufficient. Dust can be approximated from the difference between total Mass and sum of Inorganic, EC and OC. As a proxy for the chemical composition, combination of different properties can be used, e.g. size (from Extinction Angström exponent or Fine Mode fraction), absorption (from SSA or AAOD), absorption colour (Absorption Angström exponent). However, any such estimated characterization needs to be associated with a clear definition how a certain aerosol type was characterized and this should be part of the metadata in a product file." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Chlorophyll-a
ecv:Chlorophyll-a rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                           ecv:ecv-product ;
                  qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroGM-PER-L ;
                  ecv:isProductOf ecv:OceanColour ;
                  skos:definition "Concentration of chlorophyll-a pigment in the surface water." ;
                  skos:note "Ocean colour is the radiance emanating from the ocean normalized by the irradiance illuminating the ocean. Products derived from ocean colour remote sensing (OCRS) contain information on the ocean albedo and information on the constituents of the seawater, in particular, phytoplankton pigments such as chlorophyll-a." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudCover
ecv:CloudCover rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                        ecv:ecv-product ;
               ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
               skos:definition "2D field of fraction of sky filled by cloud." ;
               skos:note "These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases" ,
                         "Unitless (percentage)" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudDropEffectiveRadius
ecv:CloudDropEffectiveRadius rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                      ecv:ecv-product ;
                             qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroM ;
                             ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
                             skos:definition "Ratio of integral of water droplets size distribution in volume divided by integral in area (µm)." ;
                             skos:note "These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases. Requirements for this ECV is are for the cloud top." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudIceWaterPath
ecv:CloudIceWaterPath rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                               ecv:ecv-product ;
                      qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloGM-PER-M2 ;
                      ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
                      skos:definition "2D Field of atmospheric water in the liquid phase (precipitating or not), integrated over the total column." ;
                      skos:note "This variable is identical to the also used \"Cloud ice water total column\" which is given in g/m² and often used in NWP and climate models. The uncertainty values are below would then by re-scaled from kg/m² to g/m². These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudLiquidWaterPath
ecv:CloudLiquidWaterPath rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                  ecv:ecv-product ;
                         qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloGM-PER-M2 ;
                         ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
                         skos:definition "2D Field of atmospheric water in the liquid phase (precipitating or not), integrated over the total column." ;
                         skos:note "This variable is identical to the also used \"Cloud liquid water total column\" which is given in g/m² and often used in NWP and climate models. The uncertainty values are below would then by re- scaled from Kg m-2 to g m-2 . These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudOpticalDepth
ecv:CloudOpticalDepth rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                               ecv:ecv-product ;
                      ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
                      skos:definition "Effective depth of a cloud from the viewpoint of radiation extinction. OD = exp(-K.Δz) where K is the extinction coefficient [km-1], Δz the vertical path [km] between the base and the top of the cloud and the reference wavelength to be specified in the metadata." ;
                      skos:note "Dimensionless (percentage)" ,
                                "These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudTopHeight
ecv:CloudTopHeight rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            ecv:ecv-product ;
                   qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloM ;
                   ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
                   skos:definition "Height of the top of the cloud (highest cloud in case of multi-layer clouds." ;
                   skos:note "These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases. 3-D cloud top information are required where possible. This can be achieved via a combination of cloud optical depth vs cloud top height histograms" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#CloudTopTemperature
ecv:CloudTopTemperature rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                        qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:Clouds ;
                        skos:definition "Temperature of the top of the cloud (highest cloud in case of multi-layer clouds)." ;
                        skos:note "These requirements include: Global, continental, and regional Climate monitoring, feedback and improved knowledge about the interaction between clouds, aerosols and atmospheric gases." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Clouds
ecv:Clouds rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                    ecv:ecv-variable ;
           skos:broader ecv:AtmosphericComposition .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Cryosphere
ecv:Cryosphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                        ecv:ecv-subdomain ;
               skos:member ecv:Land .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#DewPointTemperature_nearSurface
ecv:DewPointTemperature_nearSurface rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                                    qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:SurfaceWaterVapour ;
                                    skos:definition "Temperature to which air must be cooled to become saturated with water vapor at a known height above surface, with the height specified in the metadata." ;
                                    skos:note "Observations made over the ocean are not static, being mostly recorded by mobile ships and drifting buoys (Kent et al., 2019). Requirements for marine surface observations must therefore be defined in terms of the composite accuracy and sampling of the marine observing networks to achieve comparable uncertainty thresholds at similar resolution, for example through the construction of gridded data products. Willett et al. 2008 show that spatial scales of near surface dew point temperature are comparable to those of temperature so the same horizontal resolution should be broadly applicable. Timeliness requirements are for routine applications related to climate monitoring, such as assimilation into reanalyses or the update of monitoring products. Observations that miss these timeliness requirements remain useful for some climate applications and can, for example, be used in periodic revisions to climate monitoring products." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#DissolvedInorganicCarbon-DIC
ecv:DissolvedInorganicCarbon-DIC rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                          ecv:ecv-product ;
                                 qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroMOL-PER-KiloGM ;
                                 ecv:isProductOf ecv:InorganicCarbon ;
                                 skos:definition "Sum of dissolved inorganic carbon species (CO2, HCO⁻, CO3²⁻) in water." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#DissolvedOxygenConcentration
ecv:DissolvedOxygenConcentration rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                          ecv:ecv-product ;
                                 qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroMOL-PER-KiloGM ;
                                 ecv:isProductOf ecv:Oxygen ;
                                 skos:definition "Concentration of dissolved oxygen (O₂) in the water column." ;
                                 skos:note "This Essential Ocean Variable (EOV)/ECV is a measurement of sub-surface dissolved oxygen (O₂) concentration in the ocean, expressed in units of μmol kg⁻¹. Data on dissolved oxygen is obtained by both discrete (chemical analysis) and continuous (sensor measurements) sampling performed on a number of observing platforms (ship-based, fixed-point, autonomous)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#DownwardLong-WaveIrradianceAtEarthSurface
ecv:DownwardLong-WaveIrradianceAtEarthSurface rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                       ecv:ecv-product ;
                                              qudt:hasUnit unit:W-PER-M2 ;
                                              ecv:isProductOf ecv:SurfaceRadiationBudget ;
                                              skos:definition "Flux density of radiation emitted by the gases, aerosols and clouds of the atmosphere to the Earth's surface." ;
                                              skos:note "Main driver of the uncertainty in the components of the surface radiation budget is the composition of the atmosphere (e.g. Water vapour, Aerosols, Clouds)”. The Required Measurement Uncertainty (2-sigma) (see the VIM & GUM) includes both random and systematic components. The uncertainty is meant to be an uncertainty for the measurement device / instrument / ECV algorithm. The uncertainty of spatially and temporally averaged global mean value might be smaller." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#DownwardShort-WaveIrradianceAtEarthSurface
ecv:DownwardShort-WaveIrradianceAtEarthSurface rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                        ecv:ecv-product ;
                                               qudt:hasUnit unit:W-PER-M2 ;
                                               ecv:isProductOf ecv:SurfaceRadiationBudget ;
                                               skos:definition "Flux density of the solar radiation at the Earth surface." ;
                                               skos:note "Main driver of the uncertainty in the components of the surface radiation budget is the composition of the atmosphere (e.g. Water vapour, Aerosols, Clouds)”. The Required Measurement Uncertainty (2-sigma) (see the VIM & GUM) includes both random and systematic components. The uncertainty is meant to be an uncertainty for the measurement device / instrument / ECV algorithm. The uncertainty of spatially and temporally averaged global mean value might be smaller." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#DownwardShort-WaveIrradianceAtTopOfTheAtmosphere
ecv:DownwardShort-WaveIrradianceAtTopOfTheAtmosphere rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                              ecv:ecv-product ;
                                                     qudt:hasUnit unit:W-PER-M2 ;
                                                     ecv:isProductOf ecv:EarthRadiationBudget ;
                                                     skos:definition "Flux density of the solar radiation at the top of the atmosphere." ;
                                                     skos:note "This EVC is formerly/also known as Total Solar Irradiance (TSI)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#ECV-scheme
ecv:ECV-scheme rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                        ecv:EssentialClimaticVariables .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#EarthRadiationBudget
ecv:EarthRadiationBudget rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                  ecv:ecv-variable ;
                         skos:broader ecv:UpperAtmosphere .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#EkmanCurrents
ecv:EkmanCurrents rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                           ecv:ecv-product ;
                  qudt:hasUnit unit:M-PER-SEC ;
                  ecv:isProductOf ecv:SurfaceCurrents ;
                  skos:definition "Ocean vector motion occurring over the depth of the Ekman layer as a result of the combined action of surface winds and Coriolis force." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#EvaporationFromLand
ecv:EvaporationFromLand rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                 ecv:ecv-variable ;
                        skos:broader ecv:Hydrology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Fire
ecv:Fire rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                  ecv:ecv-variable ;
         skos:broader ecv:Biology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#FireRadiativePower-FRP
ecv:FireRadiativePower-FRP rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-product ;
                           qudt:hasUnit unit:W ;
                           ecv:isProductOf ecv:Fire ;
                           skos:definition "Energy per unit time released by all fires burning within the pixel footprint. This variable is a function of actual temperature of the active fire at the satellite overpass and the proportion of the grid cell being burned." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#FractionOfAbsorbedPhotosyntheticallyActiveRadiation
ecv:FractionOfAbsorbedPhotosyntheticallyActiveRadiation rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                                                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:FractionOfAbsorbedPhotosyntheticallyActiveRadiation-FAPAR ;
                                                        skos:definition "FAPAR is defined as the fraction of photosynthetically active radiation (PAR, i.e. the solar radiation reaching the surface in the 0.4-0.7μm spectral region) that is absorbed by vegetation canopy. Both black-sky (assuming only direct radiation) and white-sky (assuming that all the incoming radiation is in the form of isotropic diffuse radiation) FAPAR values may be considered. Similarly FAPAR can also be angularly integrated or instantaneous (i.e., at the actual sun position of measurement). Leaves- only FAPAR refers to the fraction of PAR radiation absorbed by live leaves only, i.e., contributing to the photosynthetic activity within leaf cells." ;
                                                        skos:note """FAPAR plays a critical role in assessing the primary productivity of canopies, the associated fixation of atmospheric CO2 and the energy balance of the surface.
Length of record: Threshold: 20 years; Target: >40 years""" ,
                                                                  "Unit: Dimensionless" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#FractionOfAbsorbedPhotosyntheticallyActiveRadiation-FAPAR
ecv:FractionOfAbsorbedPhotosyntheticallyActiveRadiation-FAPAR rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                                       ecv:ecv-variable ;
                                                              skos:broader ecv:Biology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Freeze-Thaw
ecv:Freeze-Thaw rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                         ecv:ecv-product ;
                ecv:isProductOf ecv:SoilMoisture ;
                skos:definition "Flag indicating whether the land surface is frozen or not." ;
                skos:note "Freeze/Thaw is subsidiary variable of the ECV soil moisture. It is needed because most measurement techniques do not allow to measure soil moisture when the ground is frozen. Also, land-surface processes fundamentally change when the soil is frozen. Instead of binary values (e.g. thawed = 0 and frozen = 1) probabilities (i.e. probability that the soil is frozen) may be used." ,
                          "Unitless" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GlacierArea
ecv:GlacierArea rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                         ecv:ecv-product ;
                qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloM2 ;
                ecv:isProductOf ecv:Glaciers ;
                skos:definition "Inventory of map-projected area covered by glaciers." ;
                skos:note "Glacier area is the map-projected size of a glacier in km2. The product comes as worldwide inventory of glaciers outlines with various related attribute fields (e.g. area, elevation range, glacier characteristics). Typically, a minimum size of 0.01 or 0.02 km2 is applied, to avoid including small ice patches which do not flow and are therefore not glaciers." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GlacierElevationChange
ecv:GlacierElevationChange rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-product ;
                           qudt:hasUnit unit:M-PER-YR ;
                           ecv:isProductOf ecv:Glaciers ;
                           skos:definition "Glacier surface elevation changes from geodetic methods." ;
                           skos:note "Measured in-situ and remotely sensed using geodetic method (Cogley et al. 2011, Zemp et al. 2013)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GlacierMassChange
ecv:GlacierMassChange rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                               ecv:ecv-product ;
                      qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloGM-PER-M2 ;
                      ecv:isProductOf ecv:Glaciers ;
                      skos:definition "Glacier Mass Changes from glaciological method." ;
                      skos:note "Mass change is measured in-situ by the glaciological method (Cogley et al. 2011, Zemp et al. 2013)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Glaciers
ecv:Glaciers rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                      ecv:ecv-variable ;
             skos:broader ecv:Cryosphere .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GlobalMeanSeaLevel
ecv:GlobalMeanSeaLevel rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                ecv:ecv-product ;
                       qudt:hasUnit unit:M ;
                       ecv:isProductOf ecv:SeaLevel ;
                       skos:definition "The height of the ocean surface relative to a reference geoid." ;
                       skos:note "Estimates of the global mean sea level are obtained by averaging individual sea surface heights over the global ocean during a given period." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GroundingLineLocationAndThickness
ecv:GroundingLineLocationAndThickness rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                               ecv:ecv-product ;
                                      qudt:hasUnit unit:M ;
                                      ecv:isProductOf ecv:IceSheetsAndIceShelves ;
                                      skos:definition "Location of the line (zone) where ice outflow to an ocean begins to float, and thickness of ice at that location." ;
                                      skos:note "Unit: m (thickness), coordinates of location" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Groundwater
ecv:Groundwater rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                         ecv:ecv-variable ;
                skos:broader ecv:Hydrology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GroundwaterLevel
ecv:GroundwaterLevel rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                              ecv:ecv-product ;
                     qudt:hasUnit unit:M ;
                     ecv:isProductOf ecv:Groundwater ;
                     skos:definition "The level (depth or elevation) of the water table, the upper surface of the saturated portion of the soil or bedrock." ;
                     skos:note "Groundwater levels are measured in monitoring wells. The measurements are expressed in m (below ground surface or above sea level, depending on the reference system)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#GroundwaterStorageChange
ecv:GroundwaterStorageChange rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                      ecv:ecv-product ;
                             qudt:hasUnit unit:MilliM-PER-YR ;
                             ecv:isProductOf ecv:Groundwater ;
                             skos:definition "The volumetric loss or gain of groundwater between two times period." ;
                             skos:note "Ground water storage change is monitored at large spatial scales by satellite gravimetry. To isolate groundwater storage change from the total mass variations observed by satellite gravimetry, all other mass changes in the Earth system need to be subtracted by complementary observations or models." ,
                                       "Unit: km^3 y-1 or mm y-1" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#HCHOTroposphericColumn
ecv:HCHOTroposphericColumn rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-product ;
                           qudt:hasUnit cunit:MoleculesPerSquareCentimeter ;
                           ecv:isProductOf ecv:PrecursorsForAerosolsAndOzone ;
                           skos:definition "2D field of total amount of HCHO molecules per unit area in an atmospheric column extending from the Earth’s surface to the tropopause." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#HardCoralCoverAndComposition
ecv:HardCoralCoverAndComposition rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                          ecv:ecv-product ;
                                 qudt:hasUnit unit:PERCENT ;
                                 ecv:isProductOf ecv:MarineHabitats ;
                                 skos:definition "Percent cover of hard coral. For composition, this is broken down by taxonomic or functional groups." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#High-ResolutionFootprintAroundPointSources
ecv:High-ResolutionFootprintAroundPointSources rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                        ecv:ecv-product ;
                                               qudt:hasUnit unit:PPM ;
                                               ecv:isProductOf ecv:AnthropogenicGreenhouseGasEmissions ;
                                               skos:definition "Spatially resolved GHG emission plume around local source." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#HumanUseOfNaturalResources
ecv:HumanUseOfNaturalResources rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                        ecv:ecv-subdomain ;
                               skos:member ecv:Land .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Hydrology
ecv:Hydrology rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                       ecv:ecv-subdomain ;
              skos:member ecv:Land .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#IceSheetsAndIceShelves
ecv:IceSheetsAndIceShelves rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-variable ;
                           skos:broader ecv:Cryosphere .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#IceVelocity
ecv:IceVelocity rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                         ecv:ecv-product ;
                qudt:hasUnit unit:M-PER-YR ;
                ecv:isProductOf ecv:IceSheetsAndIceShelves ;
                skos:definition "Surface-parallel vector of the surface ice flow." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#IceVolumeChange
ecv:IceVolumeChange rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                    qudt:hasUnit cunit:kiloM3-PER-YR ;
                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:IceSheetsAndIceShelves ;
                    skos:definition "Direct measurement of local volume changes or inferred volume change from combining measurements." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#InorganicCarbon
ecv:InorganicCarbon rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                             ecv:ecv-variable ;
                    skos:broader ecv:Biogeochemical .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#IntegratedWaterVapour
ecv:IntegratedWaterVapour rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                   ecv:ecv-product ;
                          qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloGM-PER-M2 ;
                          ecv:isProductOf ecv:Upper-airWaterVapour ;
                          skos:definition "Total amount of water vapour present in a vertical atmospheric column." ;
                          skos:note "Implicit assumption that IWV is intrinsically linked to boundary layer and surface humidity given the predominance of the water vapour in these regions in contributing to the column total. Because IWV scales with temperature, uncertainty and stability should be split latitudinally. The applied values here are for mid-latitude locations. They would be stricter (more relaxed) for polar (tropical) locations and in winter than summer." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#InterceptionLoss
ecv:InterceptionLoss rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                              ecv:ecv-product ;
                     qudt:hasUnit unit:W-PER-M2 ;
                     ecv:isProductOf ecv:EvaporationFromLand ;
                     skos:definition "The component of the total latent heat flux that corresponds to the precipitation that is intercepted by vegetation and evaporated directly." ;
                     skos:note "The requirements are analogous to those of the total latent heat flux, because the applications are the same. Several studies have shown, however, that the accuracy of the latent heat flux can still be adequate despite a higher uncertainty in the evaporation components (i.e. bare soil evaporation, transpiration and interception loss) – see e.g. Miralles et al. (2016), Talsma et al. (2018). For that reason, the uncertainty goals have been subjectively relaxed based on expert judgement." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#InteriorOceanNitrousOxideN2O
ecv:InteriorOceanNitrousOxideN2O rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                          ecv:ecv-product ;
                                 qudt:hasUnit unit:NanoMOL-PER-KiloGM ;
                                 ecv:isProductOf ecv:NitrousOxide ;
                                 skos:definition "Concentration of N₂O gas in the water column." ;
                                 skos:note "Nitrous oxide (N2O) is an atmospheric trace gas which is measured in the water column of all major ocean basins at concentrations spanning three orders of magnitude. The ocean is a major source (around 25%) of N2O gas to the atmosphere." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#InteriorSalinity
ecv:InteriorSalinity rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                              ecv:ecv-product ;
                     qudt:hasUnit unit:GM-PER-KiloGM ,
                                  unit:PSU ;
                     ecv:isProductOf ecv:SubsurfaceSalinity ;
                     skos:definition "Salinity of seawater measured with depth." ;
                     skos:note "This variable is referred to as “Ocean salinity” in WMO RRR OSCAR database, and a difference between Upper (<2000 m) and Deep (>2000 m) ocean is established." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#InteriorTemperature
ecv:InteriorTemperature rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                        qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:SubsurfaceTemperature ;
                        skos:definition "Seawater temperature measured with depth." ;
                        skos:note "This variable is referred to as “Ocean temperature” in WMO RRR, and a difference between Upper (<2000 m) and Deep (>2000 m) ocean is established." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LakeIceCover-LIC
ecv:LakeIceCover-LIC rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                              ecv:ecv-product ;
                     qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloM2 ;
                     ecv:isProductOf ecv:Lakes ;
                     skos:definition "Area of lake covered by ice." ;
                     skos:note "Based on lake-wide satellite observations. In situ observations of ice cover can be temporally and spatially consistent, and therefore be useful for climate monitoring, but capture variations and trends in ice cover that are spatially limited (i.e. not lake-wide but rather representative of some limited area observable from lake shore). Lake-wide ice phenology can be derived from LIC (freeze onset to complete freeze over (CFO) dates during the freeze-up period; melt onset to water clear of ice (WCI) dates during the break-up period; and ice cover duration derived from number of days between CFO and WCI dates over an ice year) (Duguay et al., 2015). For lakes that do not form a complete ice cover every year or in some years (e.g. Laurentian Great Lakes), maximum ice cover extent (timestamped with date) is also a useful climate indicator that can be derived; similarly minimum ice extent can be derived for High Arctic lakes that do not completely lose their ice cover in summer." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LakeIceThickness-LIT
ecv:LakeIceThickness-LIT rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                  ecv:ecv-product ;
                         qudt:hasUnit unit:CentiM ;
                         ecv:isProductOf ecv:Lakes ;
                         skos:definition "Thickness of ice on a lake." ;
                         skos:note "LIT measurements are largely based on in situ observational networks. Satellite-based retrieval algorithms are under development (research stage), not operational yet. On-ice snow depth measurements are also useful for both climate monitoring as well as for assessing and improving lake models." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LakeSurfaceWaterTemperature-LSWT
ecv:LakeSurfaceWaterTemperature-LSWT rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                              ecv:ecv-product ;
                                     qudt:hasUnit unit:DEG_C ;
                                     ecv:isProductOf ecv:Lakes ;
                                     skos:definition "Temperature of the lake surface." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LakeWater-LeavingReflectance
ecv:LakeWater-LeavingReflectance rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                          ecv:ecv-product ;
                                 ecv:isProductOf ecv:Lakes ;
                                 skos:definition "Water-leaving reflectance in discrete wavebands of electromagnetic radiation from near-UV through visible to near infrared and up to shortwave infrared, fully normalized for viewing and solar incident angles." ;
                                 skos:note "Unit: Dimensionless" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LakeWaterExtent-LWE
ecv:LakeWaterExtent-LWE rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                        qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloM2 ;
                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:Lakes ;
                        skos:definition "Areal extent of the surface of a lake." ;
                        skos:note "LWE is only measurable using satellite imagery. For shallow lakes the LWE variable is more relevant than the Lake Water Level to detect climate change signal (Mason et al., 1994)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LakeWaterLevel-LWL
ecv:LakeWaterLevel-LWL rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                ecv:ecv-product ;
                       qudt:hasUnit unit:CentiM ;
                       ecv:isProductOf ecv:Lakes ;
                       skos:definition "Lake Water Level (LWL). Elevation of the free surface of a lake relative to a specified vertical datum." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Lakes
ecv:Lakes rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                   ecv:ecv-variable ;
          skos:broader ecv:Hydrology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Land
ecv:Land rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                  ecv:ecv-domain .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Land-Cover
ecv:Land-Cover rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                        ecv:ecv-product ;
               ecv:isProductOf ecv:LandCover ;
               skos:definition "Land cover is defined as the observed (bio)-physical cover on the Earth’s surface for regional and global climate applications." ;
               skos:note "Land cover can be variable in time due to land changes and phenology." ,
                         "Unit: Primary units are categories (binary variables such as forest or cropland) or continuous variables classifiers (e.g. fraction of tree canopy cover in percent). Secondary outputs include surface area of land cover/use types and land cover/use changes (in ha). UN/FAO Land Cover Classification System (LCCS) + C3/C4 sub-classification should be used with cross-walking tables to other common classifications." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LandCover
ecv:LandCover rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                       ecv:ecv-variable ;
              skos:broader ecv:Biology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LandSurfaceTemperature
ecv:LandSurfaceTemperature rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-variable ;
                           skos:broader ecv:Biology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LandSurfaceTemperature-LST
ecv:LandSurfaceTemperature-LST rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                        ecv:ecv-product ;
                               qudt:hasUnit unit:K ;
                               ecv:isProductOf ecv:LandSurfaceTemperature ;
                               skos:definition "Land Surface Temperature (LST) is a measure of how hot or cold the surface of the Earth would feel to the touch. When derived from radiometric measurements of ground-based, airborne, and spaceborne remote sensing instruments, LST is the aggregated radiometric surface temperature of the ensemble of components within the sensor field of view." ;
                               skos:note "From a climate perspective, LST is important for evaluating land surface and land-atmosphere exchange processes, constraining surface energy budgets and model parameters, and providing observations of surface temperature change both globally and in key regions." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LatentHeatFlux
ecv:LatentHeatFlux rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            ecv:ecv-product ;
                   qudt:hasUnit unit:W-PER-M2 ;
                   ecv:isProductOf ecv:EvaporationFromLand ,
                                   ecv:OceanSurfaceHeatFlux ;
                   skos:definition """Ocean: The latent heat exchanged between the ocean and atmosphere associated with the phase change from liquid to gas during evaporation of seawater or from gas to liquid during condensation. During the more common process of surface evaporation, heat is extracted from the ocean, cooling the surface ocean. The moistened parcel of air can be carried aloft and the latent heat released to the atmosphere through condensation, which plays a crucial role in cloud formation and precipitation.
Land: The land surface (terrestrial) latent heat flux is the energy flux associated with the evaporation occurring over land surfaces, and it may comprise three main sources or individual components: bare soil evaporation (direct evaporation of water from soils), interception loss (evaporation of water from wet canopies) and transpiration (plant water consumption), each of which are considered as sub-products.""" ;
                   skos:note "The net surface heat flux is the rate of exchange of heat, per unit area, crossing the sea surface from ocean to atmosphere. Sign conventions vary; heat fluxes are sometimes reported with positive values for heat into the ocean. The net heat flux is the sum of turbulent (latent and sensible) fluxes and the radiative (short wave and long wave) components. Latent heat flux is associated with the phase change of water during evaporation or condensation and proportional to evaporation. The energy required for surface evaporation cools the ocean surface and moistens the near surface air adding to its buoyancy. The moistened parcel of air can be carried aloft, and the latent heat released to the atmosphere through condensation, which plays a crucial role in cloud formation and precipitation. Surface measured precipitation is often out of balance with evaporation (P-E), which implies moisture convergence/divergence in the atmosphere. In the tropics, latent heat flux is typically an order of magnitude greater than sensible heat flux, but in polar regions they are similar in magnitude. These fluxes are major contributors to energy and moisture budgets, and are largely responsible for thermodynamic coupling of the ocean and atmosphere on all scales. Variability of these fluxes is in part related to largescale variability in weather (climate) patterns. For most regions, the two major components are the net shortwave gain by the ocean and the latent heat flux loss by the ocean." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LeafAreaIndex
ecv:LeafAreaIndex rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                           ecv:ecv-variable ;
                  skos:broader ecv:Biology .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#LeafAreaIndex-LAI
ecv:LeafAreaIndex-LAI rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                               ecv:ecv-product ;
                      qudt:hasUnit unit:M2-PER-M2 ;
                      ecv:isProductOf ecv:LeafAreaIndex ;
                      skos:definition "Leaf Area Index of a plant canopy or ecosystem is defined as one half of the total green leaf area per unit horizontal ground surface area and measures the area of leaf material present in the specified environment (projection to the underlying ground along the normal to the slope)." ;
                      skos:note "Effective Leaf Area Index is the LAI value that would produce the same indirect ground measurement as that observed assuming foliage distribution (LAIeff=LAItrue x canopy clumping index). The conversion of data measurements to true values is an essential step and requires additional information about the structure and architecture of the canopy, e.g. gap size distributions, at the appropriate spatial resolutions. Leaf Area Index controls important mass and energy exchange processes, such as radiation and rain interception, as well as photosynthesis and respiration, which couple vegetation to the climate system. Length of record: Threshold: 20 years; Target: >40 years." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Lightning
ecv:Lightning rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                       ecv:ecv-variable ;
              skos:broader ecv:UpperAtmosphere ;
              skos:definition "Total number of detected strokes in the corresponding time interval and the space unit. The space unit ‭(grid box) should be on the order of the horizontal resolution and the accumulation time to the observing cycle." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#MacroalgalCanopyCoverAndComposition
ecv:MacroalgalCanopyCoverAndComposition rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:MarineHabitats ;
                                        skos:definition "Abundance of layered macroalgal stands in marine coastal environments." ;
                                        skos:note "Note Percent cover measured within quadrats (e.g., 0.5 x 0.5 m) or transects (e.g., 50 x 5 m). For large macroalgae such as kelps, abundance can be measured as number of individuals per area." ,
                                                  "Unit: percent or number of individuals/area" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#MangroveCoverAndComposition
ecv:MangroveCoverAndComposition rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                         ecv:ecv-product ;
                                ecv:isProductOf ecv:MarineHabitats ;
                                skos:definition "Extent of mangroves and species types in coastal environments (percent or ha and number of species per area)." ;
                                skos:note "Unit: Extent measured in quadrats (e.g. 10x10m), or by pixels (e.g. 30x30m)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#MapsOfHigh-ResolutionLandCover
ecv:MapsOfHigh-ResolutionLandCover rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                            ecv:ecv-product ;
                                   ecv:isProductOf ecv:LandCover ;
                                   skos:definition "High Resolution Land Cover is the observed (bio)-physical cover on the Earth’s surface for monitoring changes at local scales (suitable for adaptation and mitigation)." ;
                                   skos:note "It can also be variable in time due to land changes and phenology." ,
                                             "Unit: Primary units are categories (binary variables such as forest or cropland) or continuous variables classifiers (e.g. fraction of tree canopy cover in percent). Secondary outputs include surface area of land cover/use types and land cover/use changes (in ha)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#MapsOfKeyIPCCLandClasses-ChangesAndLandManagementTypes
ecv:MapsOfKeyIPCCLandClasses-ChangesAndLandManagementTypes rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                                    ecv:ecv-product ;
                                                           ecv:isProductOf ecv:LandCover ;
                                                           skos:definition "Land cover classes to be used for the estimation of GHG emissions and removals following the IPCC guidelines." ;
                                                           skos:note "It can also be variable in time due to land changes and phenology. Crucially, this table refers to change products." ,
                                                                     "Unit: Primary units are categories (binary variables such as forest or cropland) or continuous variables classifiers (e.g. fraction of tree canopy cover in percent). Secondary outputs include surface area of land cover/use types and land cover/use changes (in ha)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#MarineHabitats
ecv:MarineHabitats rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            ecv:ecv-variable ;
                   skos:broader ecv:Biological-Ecosystems ;
                   skos:definition "Extent of mangroves and species types in coastal environments ‭(percent or ha and number of species per area)." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#MineralSoilBulkDensity
ecv:MineralSoilBulkDensity rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                    ecv:ecv-product ;
                           qudt:hasUnit unit:KiloGM-PER-M3 ;
                           ecv:isProductOf ecv:SoilCarbon ;
                           skos:definition "Bulk density of dry soil averaged over the topmost 30 cm and topmost 1 m." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Multi-wavelengthAerosolOpticalDepth
ecv:Multi-wavelengthAerosolOpticalDepth rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                 ecv:ecv-product ;
                                        ecv:isProductOf ecv:Aerosols ;
                                        skos:definition "Multi-wavelength AOD is the spectral dependent aerosol extinction coefficient integrated over the geometrical path length. (see note)" ;
                                        skos:note "Aerosol Optical Depth quantifies the extinction of the radiation while propagating in an aerosol layer and reflects the aerosol loading information in the view of remote sensing measurement. AOD varies with wavelength and this variation is related to the aerosol size and type. The GAW guidelines recommend AOD be measured at 3 or more wavelengths among 368, 412, 500, 675, 778, and 862 nm with a bandwidth of 5nm. 1) under some assumptions of aerosol models and surface reflectances, spectral-dependence of AOD permits retrieval of Fine-AOD and Coarse-AOD, defined as the fraction of total aerosol optical depth attributed to the “non-dust” and \"dust\" aerosols, respectively, which are important parameters to distinguish aerosol type. Also sea-salt is part of the coarse mode AOD 2) The absorption aerosol optical depth (AAOD) is the fraction of AOD related to light absorption and is defined as AAOD=(1−ωo)×AOD where ωo is the column integrated aerosol single scattering albedo." ,
                                                  "Unit: Dimensionless" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#N2OAir-seaFlux
ecv:N2OAir-seaFlux rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            ecv:ecv-product ;
                   qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroMOL-PER-M2-DAY ;
                   ecv:isProductOf ecv:NitrousOxide ;
                   skos:definition "Amount of N₂O produced per area per year." ;
                   skos:note "Unit: MicroMOL-PER-M2-YEAR" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#N2OMoleFraction
ecv:N2OMoleFraction rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                    qudt:hasUnit unit:PPB ;
                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:CarbonDioxideMethaneAndOtherGreenhouseGases ;
                    skos:definition "3D field of amount of N2O (expressed in moles) divided by the total amount of all constituents in dry air (also expressed in moles)." ;
                    skos:note "N2O was not an ECV product in the GCOS IP but should be added as it is a strong GHG." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#NO2MoleFraction
ecv:NO2MoleFraction rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                    qudt:hasUnit unit:PPB ;
                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:PrecursorsForAerosolsAndOzone ;
                    skos:definition "3D field of amount of NO2 (expressed in moles) divided by the total amount of all constituents in dry air (also expressed in moles) – in stratosphere." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#NO2TroposphericColumn
ecv:NO2TroposphericColumn rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                   ecv:ecv-product ;
                          qudt:hasUnit cunit:MoleculesPerSquareCentimeter ;
                          ecv:isProductOf ecv:PrecursorsForAerosolsAndOzone ;
                          skos:definition "2D field of total amount of NO2 molecules per unit area in an atmospheric column extending from the Earth’s surface to the tropopause." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Nitrate
ecv:Nitrate rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                     ecv:ecv-product ;
            qudt:hasUnit unit:MicroMOL-PER-KiloGM ;
            ecv:isProductOf ecv:Nutrients ;
            skos:definition "Concentration of NO₃ in the water column." ;
            skos:note "The availability of nutrients in seawater is estimated from measurements of concentration of inorganic macronutrients: nitrate (NO₃), phosphate (PO₄), silicic acid (Si(OH)₄), ammonium (NH₄), and nitrite (NO₂), expressed in umol kg⁻¹ of seawater. Nutrients ECV products are primarily obtained from discrete sample measurements using analytical chemical methods (colorimetric reactions) but nitrate concentration is also measured by sensors using the ultraviolet absorption method. Linear combination of nitrate and phosphate, defined as N*, and the difference between silicic acid and nitrate concentrations, Si*, provide estimates of nutrient supply/removal relative to global Redfield stoichiometry and are widely used for mapping and detecting trends in global nutrient cycling." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#NitrousOxide
ecv:NitrousOxide rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                          ecv:ecv-variable ;
                 skos:broader ecv:Biogeochemical ;
                 skos:definition "Concentration of N₂O gas in the water column." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#NumberOfCloudCondensationNuclei
ecv:NumberOfCloudCondensationNuclei rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                             ecv:ecv-product ;
                                    ecv:isProductOf ecv:Aerosols ;
                                    skos:definition "Number of aerosol particles which can activate to a cloud droplet at a given supersaturations of water. CCN is often indicated as a percent of the total CN for specific supersaturation typical of atmospheric cloud formation." ;
                                    skos:note "CCN depends on the supersaturation. Whenever provision of CCN for a range of supersaturation is not available, a typical value of 0.5% can be used as typical supersaturation under atmospheric conditions. The CCN number concentration can be approximated by the fraction of particles larger than a given diameter from the particle number size distribution, generally the number of particles larger than 100 nm, which provide a good approximation of particles activated at « typical » supersaturation. Where no other data are available, fine mode AOD can be used as a qualitative proxy for CCN" ,
                                              "Unit: Dimensionless" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/crima/crima-ecv#Nutrients
ecv:Nutrients rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                       ecv:ecv-variable ;
              skos:broader ecv:Biogeochemical ;
              skos:definition "Concentration of Si(OH)₄ in the water column." .


